cation. While the plaintiffs have won in the majority of these cases, the decisions are often branded “judicial activism”—a stigma that has reduced their impact. To counter the charge, Michael A. Rebell persuasively defends the courts’ authority and responsibility to pursue the goal of educational equity. He envisions their ideal role as supervisory, and in Courts and Kids he offers innovative recommendations on how the courts can collaborate with the executive and legislative branches to create a truly democratic educational system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDiscrimination in educationxLaw and legislationxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in educationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationxUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aEducational law and legislationxUnited States. 0aEducational law and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, educational, equal, equity, state, regional, courtroom, courts, legal, law, litigation, lawyers, judge, jury, federal, government, school, desegregation, segregation, civil rights, brown, board, precedent, ruling, 1970s, finance, financial, income, wealth, economy, economics, minority, access, judicial, activism, activist, democratic, funding, classroom, student, teacher.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022670619140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226706184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226706184/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles